  "body": "In-Class Exercises   Lattice of subgroups of   A diamond-shaped lattice with four vertices.      Consider the lattices of divisors of 6, 12, 16, and 30, with the partial ordering divides .  Determine which elements of have a complement.  Determine which elements of have a complement.  Determine which elements of have a complement.  Determine which elements of have a complement.  Given that is always a distributive lattice, for what values of do you suppose is a boolean algebra?    Recall that if is a finite group and , the cyclic subgroup generated by is , which is a finite set since you eventually get to the identity and can stop listing elements. For example, if the group is , there are four different cyclic subgroups: , , , and . The other two elements of , 4 and 5 generate subgroups that are equal to the subgroups generated by 2 and 1, respectively. The Hasse diagram for this set of subgroups with is    List the distinct cyclic subgroups generated by elements of . The set of subgroups you've found is a lattice with the partial ordering . Draw the Hasse diagram for this poset.  Do the same with the cyclic subgroups generated by elements of .  Do the same with the cyclic subgroups generated by elements of .  Any general observations from the three cases?     "
